    "content_hash": "sha256:b3eba3a0204d1c49dc5726062d3cb98a8c656cbcb25cee73064cc3d941a23b84",
    "summary": "Jesus of Nazareth (c. 4 BC – c. 30–33 AD) was a Jewish preacher and teacher from Galilee whose life, teachings, death, and reported resurrection became the foundation of Christianity — the world's largest religion with over 2 billion adherents. Virtually all historians agree on a core of biographical facts: Jesus was baptized by John the Baptist, gathered disciples, taught throughout Galilee and Judea, and was crucified under the Roman prefect Pontius Pilate. His followers' belief that he rose from the dead distinguishes the Christian claim about him from historical consensus.\n\nJesus's teachings, as recorded in the Gospels (written 40–100 years after his death), center on the Kingdom of God, love of neighbor and enemy, forgiveness, care for the poor and marginalized, and the fulfillment of Jewish prophetic expectations. He taught in parables — compressed narratives of extraordinary psychological and moral depth — and gathered around him a community that cut across social boundaries of gender, class, and religious status. His conflicts with Jewish religious authorities and the Roman administration led to his [[event:2013|Crucifixion of Jesus]], which his followers interpreted not as defeat but as sacrificial atonement, followed by resurrection and ascension.\n\nThe historical Jesus is partially recoverable through careful critical analysis of the Gospels, Paul's letters (written 20–30 years after the crucifixion), and fragmentary references in Josephus and Tacitus. The Christ of Christian faith — divine Son of God, second person of the Trinity — is a theological development of this historical core, debated and defined over centuries of church councils. Whatever the historical judgment, Jesus's influence on world history is unparalleled: his name and image have shaped more human lives, art, architecture, philosophy, and politics than any other single figure.",
